For Office workers, the less hours you work, the better? As the Koreans will tell you, not necessarily. The 52-hour work schedule, which has been in place for nearly two years, is gradually covering all walks of life in South Korea, giving workers more time to return to their families, but with it comes another side of the double-edged sword.

On February 4th South Korea proposed a special measure to deal with an outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia in China: Lifting restrictions on working hours for manufacturers of face masks and health care products. According to the Korean Labour Standards Act, in the event of a disaster or major incident, the type of work enterprise may request an extension of working hours, provided that the employee's consent and the approval of the Ministry of Labour are obtained.

Because of the impact of the outbreak on the supply chain, South Korean car companies also asked to relax the 52-hour working time limit to avoid the phenomenon of insufficient supply. Hyundai and KIA, two of South Korea's biggest carmakers, are facing a production crisis brought on by the collapse of their supply chains, with Hyundai having suspended some production. South Korean auto parts manufacturers said Wednesday at a meeting with the Ministry of Trade, Industry and energy that the maximum working hours limit the use of limited manpower to increase production.

The Republic of Korea introduced a 52-hour work week in July 2018 and expanded the scope of implementation from public institutions and large enterprises to small and medium-sized enterprises with more than 50 employees and less than 300 employees from January 2020. But these companies will enjoy a one-year transition period, and companies that enjoy the benefits of the transition period will be excluded from regulation.

By 2021, the rule will cover companies with fewer than 49 employees. The system applies to 21 industries, including bus companies, restaurants, bars, wholesale and retail stores. But on Jan. 31, South Korea's Ministry of Employment and Labor introduced a supplemental rule that exempts institutions and companies involved in key research projects from the maximum working hours limit if their applications are approved.

The maximum working week is 52 hours, with 40 working days, or 8 hours a day, capped at 12 on weekends. This sounds like a reasonable and common working time rule. But that is 16 hours less than the previous peak of 68 hours a week.

The "52-hour Work Day" is part of a campaign pledge by South Korea's President, Moon jae-in, to reduce what South Koreans often call "inhuman long" working hours and improve work-life balance.

In 2017, South Korea was the second-largest OECD member with 2,024 hours of work per person per year, nearly 300 hours above the OECD average. Overwork triggered by the "overwork death" and even "overwork suicide" one after another, so that the South Korean government had to change. In March 2018, a law to shorten working hours was passed by an overwhelming majority in the Korean National Assembly.

The working hours of South Koreans have changed dramatically since the new law came into force. For the first time in 2018, the average worker worked 1,986 hours, less than 2,000, according to data released by the Labor Ministry. Moon's government is trying to reduce that to 1,800 hours by 2022. Some companies take measures such as turning off computers automatically to "force" employees to leave work.

When working hours are reduced, family time is increased. Private spending on education and entertainment grew at its fastest pace in nine years and seven years, respectively, in 2018, according to the Central Bank.

The South Korean government believes this will also help boost the country's birth rate. South Korea's birth rate has been declining, even falling below 1 in 2018, becoming the world's first country with zero births.

But the "load-shedding" rule has left some South Koreans unhappy, mainly because overtime pay has shrunk along with hours worked. Some people claim that they are working fewer hours, but not fewer hours, which means they have to work overtime at home for no pay.

The impact of the new rules on earnings is more pronounced among workers in manufacturing. An employee at a manufacturing company said he lost about 1 million won (6,000 yuan) in monthly income after the new rules came into effect, according to Moniys, a financial weekly. In May 2019, the bus drivers'union in South Korea also went on strike to express its dissatisfaction with the working hours regulations.

In addition to South Koreans, such regulations have also become an important incentive for many foreign workers to leave their jobs and change jobs. The latest statistics from the Ministry of Employment and Labor show that in 2020, only 86.2 percent of small and medium-sized enterprises applied for foreign jobs. The companies used to employ about 14,000 foreign workers, but only 12,000 have applied.

Under the 2020 plan for the use of foreign labor resources, the government will introduce 56,000 foreign workers next year through the "employment permit system" (E-9 visa) , of which 40,700 are in the manufacturing sector. The number of imported workers has remained at that level for four years in a row.

For some small and medium-sized enterprises, labor cost pressure is also increasing with the reduction of labor time. Some business owners said that the employment of foreign workers mostly for Koreans do not want to work, as labor costs rise, and now under the regulations can not meet some workers to earn more overtime requirements, only active or passive job reduction.

"Korea Economy" reported on the 11th that a raw material supplier for shipbuilding in Busan said that with the recent introduction of various government regulations, benefits such as room and board, overtime and piece-rate incentives for foreign workers have all disappeared. With the implementation of the 52-hour Work Week, foreign workers have conflicts with their companies.

More to the government's surprise, the new rules have also had a negative impact on South Korea's overall employment situation. The Statistics Office of Korea released statistics in March 2019, showing that the total employment of large enterprises with more than 300 employees in Korea in February 2019 was 2.459 million, compared with June 2018, before the introduction of the 52-hour Work Day, 106,000 in eight months.

Kanemoto, a professor of economics at Information Revolution in South Korea, said the 52 hour work week was introduced at a time when the growth of the Information revolution has led to an acceleration in the replacement of the labor force, the sharp rise in labor costs has prompted businesses to replace Labor with equipment, which has also led to a steady decline in jobs.
